const under = cobraVsMarketplace({ cobraSource: 'known', cobraValue: 750, household: 'single', householdSize: 1, estimatedMAGI: 42000, marketplaceBenchmarkMonthly: 480, coverageHorizonMonths: 12 });
const over = cobraVsMarketplace({ cobraSource: 'known', cobraValue: 750, household: 'single', householdSize: 1, estimatedMAGI: 70000, marketplaceBenchmarkMonthly: 480, coverageHorizonMonths: 12 });
---

<Base
  title="COBRA or marketplace after a layoff (2026 rules)"
  description="With the enhanced ACA subsidies expired for 2026, the 400% FPL cliff decides whether COBRA or the marketplace wins after a layoff. Here's the 2026 math."
>
  <section class="hero">
    <p class="hero-label">2026 · scenario</p>
    <h1>COBRA or the marketplace after a layoff?</h1>
    <p class="tagline">The 2026 answer hinges on one number the old advice ignores: whether your income lands under the 400% poverty-level subsidy cliff, which is back this year.</p>
  </section>

  <p>
    Most COBRA-vs-marketplace advice on the web is stale, because the rules changed for 2026. The enhanced premium tax
    credits that had removed the subsidy cliff expired on 31 December 2025. So for 2026 the hard <strong>400% federal
    poverty level cliff is back</strong>: under it, marketplace subsidies can make coverage far cheaper than COBRA;
    over it by a single dollar, the subsidy is $0 and the comparison flips. A layoff year — often a lower-income year —
    is exactly when this cuts in your favor.
  </p>

  <h2>Same person, two income levels</h2>
  <p>A single filer, COBRA at {formatMoney(750)}/month, a {formatMoney(480)} benchmark marketplace plan, over 12 months:</p>
  <table class="data-table">
    <thead><tr><th>2026 income</th><th>COBRA (12 mo)</th><th>Marketplace net (12 mo)</th><th>Cheaper</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>{formatMoney(42000)} (under the cliff)</td><td>{formatMoney(under.cobraTotal)}</td><td>{formatMoney(under.marketplaceTotal)}</td><td>{under.cheaper} by {formatMoney(under.savingsOverHorizon)}</td></tr>
      <tr><td>{formatMoney(70000)} (over the cliff)</td><td>{formatMoney(over.cobraTotal)}</td><td>{formatMoney(over.marketplaceTotal)}</td><td>{over.cheaper} by {formatMoney(over.savingsOverHorizon)}</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
  <p>
    At {formatMoney(42000)} a subsidy makes the marketplace much cheaper; at {formatMoney(70000)} — over the cliff —
    the subsidy vanishes and the gap narrows. The exact same plans, a different answer, decided entirely by whether
    income clears 400% of poverty.
  </p>

  <h2>The wait-and-see move</h2>
  <p>
    You have 60 days to elect COBRA, and it's retroactive to your loss date. So a healthy person can decline COBRA at
    first, shop the marketplace, and still fall back on COBRA (paying the back premiums) if a medical need arises inside
    the window. One caveat: once enrolled in COBRA, a single late payment terminates it.
  </p>

  <h2>Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq">
    <h3>What changed for 2026?</h3>
    <p data-review="legal">The enhanced premium tax credits (which had removed the 400% FPL cliff since 2021) expired
      at the end of 2025. For 2026, pre-2021 rules apply: subsidies phase out entirely above 400% of poverty. Verified
      2026-07-24 — Congress had not enacted an extension.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="faq">
    <h3>Does a severance lump sum affect this?</h3>
    <p data-review="legal">Yes — a lump sum can spike your income over the cliff for that year. Spreading severance
      across two tax years, or timing marketplace enrollment, can keep you under 400% FPL. See <a href="/lump-sum-vs-installment-severance/">lump sum vs installments</a>.</p>
  </div>

